Solution Part 2: Adding a Live Region and Focus Management to the Slideshow

05
On this page
  1. Adding a Close Fullscreen Button
  2. Creating a Live Region
  3. Wire Up Focus Management
  4. Checking Our Work
    1. Compare Behavior Without the Application Role

When we exit fullscreen mode, we want the user’s focus to be returned to the slideshow. But first, there should be a keyboard- and screen reader-interactive button for getting out of fullscreen mode in the first place.

Adding a Close Fullscreen Button

Inside of the inspiration-slideshow div but above the slideshow container around line 80, let’s add a new button for closing the fullscreen mode.

We’ll give it an ARIA label and set its click handler to the closeFullScreen function.

There’s already some CSS written for it, so we can add the btn-slideshow-close class to the button. The CSS features a rule that uses the before psuedo-element to add an “X” before a span with a class of icon inside of the button.

span.icon:before {
	content: 'X';
	display: block;
}
span.icon:before {
	content: 'X';
	display: block;
}

Because we don’t want a screen reader to announce the X, we’ll set aria-hidden="true" on the span. The accessible name will instead come from the aria-label on the wrapping button element.

Here’s the code for the completed exit fullscreen button:

<button
  aria-label="Close Full Screen mode"
  className="btn-slideshow-close"
  onClick={closeFullScreen}
  ref={btnCloseRef}
>
  <span aria-hidden="true" className="icon"></span>
</button>
<button
  aria-label="Close Full Screen mode"
  className="btn-slideshow-close"
  onClick={closeFullScreen}
  ref={btnCloseRef}
>
  <span aria-hidden="true" className="icon"></span>
</button>

Creating a Live Region

Let’s turn the slideshow container into an ARIA live region that makes announcements as the images cycle through.

On that div, add aria-live="polite". This tells the screenreader not to announce anything until most other announcements have concluded, rather than interrupting.

The ARIA role will be set conditionally. If the user is in fullscreen mode, the role will be application. Otherwise, it could use a role of region.

We’ll also add aria-roledescription , which is a property we haven’t seen yet. This allows us to fill in an arbitrary description of what the element with the role is, beyond what is available from the standard set of ARIA roles. For this component, a description of “Image Slideshow” will work.

The last thing we’ll set is a tabindex of -1 and set a ref to the slideshowRef that was already set up in our starting point.

This will keep the container out of the tab order since a div shouldn’t be focusable by default, but will still allow us to use scripting to reliably move focus to it.

Here’s what the container div looks like after our updates:

<button
  aria-label="Close Full Screen mode"
  className="btn-slideshow-close"
  onClick={closeFullScreen}
  ref={btnCloseRef}
>
  <span aria-hidden="true" className="icon"></span>
</button>
<button
  aria-label="Close Full Screen mode"
  className="btn-slideshow-close"
  onClick={closeFullScreen}
  ref={btnCloseRef}
>
  <span aria-hidden="true" className="icon"></span>
</button>

Wire Up Focus Management

When the user opens the slideshow in fullscreen mode, we should send focus into the slideshow container.

Similarly to what we did in previous lessons, we’ll use a ref to allow us to leverage the DOM’s focus API in React. The difference this time is that we’re using a single ref instead of an array of refs.

Up in the enterFullScreen function, we will add a call to slideshowRef.current.focus().

The starting point of the app already had a btnFullScreenRef set up, so we can send focus to it when fullscreen mode is closed.

The fullscreen methods look like this now:

const enterFullScreen = () => {
  setFullScreenMode(true)
  slideshowRef.current.focus()
}
const closeFullScreen = () => {
  setFullScreenMode(false)
  btnFullScreenRef.current.focus()
}
const enterFullScreen = () => {
  setFullScreenMode(true)
  slideshowRef.current.focus()
}
const closeFullScreen = () => {
  setFullScreenMode(false)
  btnFullScreenRef.current.focus()
}

Checking Our Work

Firing up NVDA in Windows, we can check our work so far.

Fullscreen mode works! We’re able to navigate through the slideshow which triggers screen reader announcements.

Compare Behavior Without the Application Role

Deleting the role="application" from the slideshow will change how the screen reader behaves.

As mentioned before, having role="application" changes the way the screen reader interacts with the page. You need to be deliberate with your usage!
